🌿 ब्रह्मगीता – ऐन्दवोपाख्यानम् (सर्ग १७८)
भाग ६ : केवल चेतना ही सत्य है
Brahma Gītā – Aindava Upākhyāna (Sarga 178)
Part Six: Consciousness Alone Is Real
मूल श्लोक
अन्तःकरणभूतादि मृत्काष्ठदृषदादि वा।
सर्वं शून्यमशून्यं च चेतनं विद्धि नेतरत्॥२५॥
तत्रैवमैन्दवाख्यानं शृणु श्रवणभूषणम्।
मया च पूर्वमुक्तं तत्किञ्चान्यदभिवर्ण्यते॥२६॥
तथापि वर्तमानोक्तप्रश्नबोधाय तच्छृणु।
यथेदं सर्वमद्र्यादि चिदित्येव तु भोत्स्यते॥२७॥

🌿 हिन्दी भावार्थ
अब श्रीवसिष्ठजी अपने उपदेश के शिखर पर पहुँचते हैं।
वे अत्यन्त स्पष्ट शब्दों में कहते हैं—
हे राम!
अन्तःकरण,
पञ्चमहाभूत,
मिट्टी,
लकड़ी,
पत्थर,
पर्वत,
और सम्पूर्ण दृश्य जगत—
इन सबको शून्य समझो।
यहाँ "शून्य" का अर्थ पूर्ण अभाव नहीं है।
इसका अर्थ है—
इनकी अपनी कोई स्वतन्त्र सत्ता नहीं है।
जिस प्रकार स्वप्न का नगर जागने पर स्वतन्त्र नहीं रहता,
उसी प्रकार यह सम्पूर्ण जगत भी अपने आप में सत्य नहीं है।
केवल एक ही वस्तु अशून्य है—
चेतना।
वही नित्य है।
वही स्वयंप्रकाश है।
वही सब अनुभवों का आधार है।
फिर श्रीवसिष्ठ कहते हैं—
अब मैं तुम्हें पुनः ऐन्दवोपाख्यान सुनाऊँगा।
यद्यपि इसे पहले भी उत्पत्ति प्रकरण में कहा था,
किन्तु उस समय उसका उद्देश्य यह दिखाना था कि जगत मनोमात्र है।
अब उसका उद्देश्य और भी उच्च है—
यह सिद्ध करना कि
सम्पूर्ण जगत चिन्मात्र है।
इसलिए यह पुनरुक्ति नहीं,
बल्कि गहनतर शिक्षा है।

🌿 English Reflection
Sage Vasiṣṭha now reaches one of the boldest declarations in the entire Yoga Vāsiṣṭha.
He tells Rama:
"Mind,
elements,
wood,
stone,
earth,
and every object you perceive—
regard them as empty."
But this "emptiness" does not mean absolute non-existence.
It means they possess no independent reality of their own.
Their existence is entirely dependent upon Consciousness.
Only Consciousness is never absent.
Only Consciousness illumines every experience.
Only Consciousness remains unchanged through waking,
dream,
and deep sleep.
Vasiṣṭha then announces that he will narrate once again the famous Aindava Upākhyāna.
He explains why.
Previously it illustrated that the universe is mind-born.
Now it will reveal an even deeper truth—
Mind itself is nothing other than Consciousness appearing in diverse forms.

🌿 Vedantic Insight
This is one of the subtle advances in Advaita.
First the seeker learns:
The world appears in the mind.
Later he discovers:
The mind itself appears in Consciousness.
Thus the journey is:
World → Mind → Consciousness.
Nothing remains outside Consciousness.
Nothing ever departs from Consciousness.
The apparent many are but names and forms upon the One.

🌿 Practical Contemplation
Today observe everything you encounter—
your body,
your thoughts,
the people you meet,
the sounds around you.
Instead of asking,
"What is this?"
Ask,
"In what is this appearing?"
Every perception appears,
abides,
and disappears in Awareness.
Awareness alone never comes,
never goes,
never changes.

🌸 Living Vedanta Library Conclusion
Maharshi Vasiṣṭha does not ask us to reject the world.
He asks us to see it correctly.
The universe is not denied.
Its imagined independence is denied.
The wave is never separate from the ocean.
The ornament is never separate from gold.
The dream is never separate from the dreamer's mind.
Likewise,
the universe is never separate from Consciousness.
Therefore,
the seeker who knows Consciousness
knows everything.
Consciousness alone is the unchanging Reality.
Everything else shines by Its borrowed light.
सर्वं खल्विदं ब्रह्म।
All this indeed is Brahman.
